<DESCRIPT>  ARTS; FINANCE; PROGRAM  </DESCRIPT>
<LEADPARA>  CAROLE Minton, a former IBM executive, has been appointed executive director
of the Arts Fund, a new private program to help create an endowment and cash
reserve for Santa Clara County's major arts groups.;    A campaign to launch
the fund is set to begin in the fall. The amount needed to stabilize the
county's arts institutions is estimated to be $18 million to $21 million. The
fund hopes to raise a part of that total.  </LEADPARA>
<SECTION>  Living  </SECTION>
<HEADLINE>  ARTS FUND-RAISING GROUP NAMES ITS FIRST DIRECTOR  </HEADLINE>
<MEMO>  The Arts  </MEMO>
<TEXT>     The money will be used to pay off accumulated debts and establish a cash
reserve and a long-term endowment for the Children's Discovery Museum of San
Jose, Opera San Jose, San Jose Civic Light Opera, San Jose Cleveland Ballet,
San Jose Museum of Art, San Jose Repertory Theatre, San Jose Symphony,
TheatreWorks of Palo Alto, Triton Museum of Art in Santa Clara and Villa
Montalvo in Saratoga, as well as smaller arts groups served by the Arts
Council of Santa Clara County.;    Minton has been an active board member of
San Jose Cleveland Ballet and the San Jose Museum of Art.;    Her assistant
director is Linda Gardner, who has worked in the development office of Santa
Clara University.;  Arts council grants;    The California Arts Council has
awarded $59,650 in basic operating support to the Arts Council of Santa Clara
County and $59,156 to the Cultural Council of Santa Cruz County. Both grants
were given under the State/Local Partnership program and were among the top 10
awarded to California's 55 county or city arts agencies. The Alameda County
Arts Commission was given $30,000 and the Arts Council of San Mateo County
$5,000.;    El Teatro Campesino has received a $25,000 challenge grant from
the California Arts Council to tour its productions of "Simply Maria" and
"Soldado Razo." The grant requires a 2-to-1 match. San Jose Repertory Theatre
received $2,500 (to be matched 3-to-1) to implement a new program for
hearing-impaired audiences.;    The largest challenge grants in this round
went to Oakland Ballet and the Old Globe Theater of San Diego, which each
received $85,000. Oakland Ballet will use its grant, which must be matched
3-to-1, to document its repertory by the late Eugene Loring, choreographer of
"Billy the Kid.";    Overall, the California Arts Council awarded $818,000 in
challenge grants to 26 arts groups across the state.  </TEXT>
